sec.p:
Sesquiterpene lactones (STL) are one of the largest groups of secondary metabolites in higher plants. They are defined by a 15 carbon backbone and a heterocyclic lactone ring which derives from an internal esterfication (

; 

). Compounds with an α-methylene-γ-lactone mojety usually show a wide range of bioactivities due to the electron affinity of the oxygen atoms in the lactone ring, which enables Michael 
type
addition to bionucleophils (

). Mostly, STL are attributed to secretory tissues of 
Asteraceae
and 
Apiaceae
where they serve as protectants against herbivory (

). In sunflower, derivatives of eupatolide (8β-hydroxycostunolide) occur highly concentrated in socalled capitate glandular trichomes (

; 

; 

). These biseriate multicellular trichomes are typical for many 
Asteraceae
, and in sunflower they develop very early on leave primordia (

, 

; 

) and on anthers, where they form a bitter and toxic barrier against predators (

). However, there is evidence, that STL can also be produced in inner tissues of sunflower, where they are found in 1000- fold lower concentrations and apparently have a physiological function in plant growth processes. So 8-epixanthatin, a xanthanolide-type STL was found in sunflower hypocotyls (Yokotani-Tomita et al., 1997) and seems to be involved in the phototropism of young seedlings (

). More recently, the guaianolide-type dehydrocostuslactone (

), the germacranolide-type costunolide and an additional xanthanolide named tomentosin (

) were found in sunflower roots and root exsudates where these STL trigger the germination and host recognition of broomrape, 

Orobanche cumana

. This shows the high signalling capacity of STL when acting in very low concentrations. Costunolide and its derivatives, such as dehydrocostuslactone, have been reported to inibit polar auxin transport in seedlings (

; 

; 

), thus confirming the possibility of a natural function of STL in plant growth regulation as suggested earlier (

; 

).

The biosynthetic route to costunolide is well established for most Astereaceae lineages. All 
Asteraceae
possess the genes to produce the precursor, germacrene A acid, from farnesyl-diphospahte (FPP) (

, 

): Germacrene A synthase (GAS) converts FPP to germacrene A and germacrene A oxidase (GAO) catalyzes the subsequent three-step oxidation to germacrene A acid (GAA) (

; 

, 

). 

expressed the first costunolide synthase (LsCOS) from 

Lactuca sativa

in combination with sunflower HaGAS and HaGAO in yeast cells. It was shown that the enzyme introduces a 6α-hydroxy-group which spontaneusly cyclizes germacrene A acid to costunoilde. EST sequence comparison showed that most 
Asteraceae
lineages possess LsCOS homologs and some of these have subsequently been characterized (

; 

; 

). However, in sunflower and related species of the Heliantheae tribe, LsCOS homologs were absent, whereas ESTs homolgous to HaG8H could be found (

). Most recently, it was shown that the STL present in sunflower capitate glandular trichomes are formed via 6α-hydroxylation of 8sshydroxy-germacrene A acid by means of the socalled eupatolide synthase HaES (

). The formation of costunolide (without 8β-hydroxy group) and dehydrocostuslactone in inner tissues of sunflower remained elusive, although, a costunolide 14-hydroxylase was recently found in sunflower (

). Therefore, we screened additional P450 sequences from public sunflower transcriptomic database to search for candidate enzymes for the final step in costunolide synthesis. CYP71BL9, a homolog to HaG8H was identified and showed the capacity to hydroxylate germacrene A acid in 6α position, the prerequisite for the subsequent lactonization to costunolide. This 

Helianthus annuus

costunolide synthase (HaCOS, CYP71BL9) is characterized here. We also show, how two alternative pathways can lead to the same end product eupatolide and that the reconstruction in a yeast system can lead to unusual previously undescribed products.

After CYP71BL9 was shown to convert germacrene A acid into costunolide we investigated if the co-expression of CYP71BL9 with the germacrene A acid 8β-hydroxylase (CYP71BL1) would lead to new enzyme products. Indeed, the introduction of CYP71BL9 [p19/ DXS + HaGAS1 + HaGAO + HaG8H + CYP71BL9] led to the formation of eupatolide which was found as cystein- and glutathion-adduct in 
HPLC
diagrams (peak 
d
and 
h
in 
Fig. 3A–E
). The negative control [p19/DXS + HaGAS1 + HaGAO + HaG8H] did not show these products. The identity of eupatolide-adducts was confirmed by comparison to synthetic adducts (
Fig. S4
and Fig. S5). As a main intermediate product, costunolide-cysteine was detected (
Fig. 3A
, peak 
a
). This was in contrast to the previously described co-expression of HaG8H with 

H. annuus

eupatolide synthase HaES (

) which also led to the production of eupatolide, but without forming costunolide adducts. Instead, the inunolide SH adducts inunolide-cystein and inunolide-GSH (
Fig. 3A
, peak 
l
and 
m
) were found and four peak tandems that were tentatively assigned to eudesmanolide rearrangement products of eupatolide-SH adducts (

). Apparently, the combination of HaG8H and HaES, as well as HaG8H and CYP71BL9 downstream of GAA lead to the production of eupatolide, but on different biosynthetic routes. When HaG8H and HaES were expressed together, GAA was converted to 8β-OH-GAA. 8β-OHGAA then partly cyclized to inunolide and partly was converted by HaES to eupatolide. No costunolide or its SH adducts were detected in plants expressing this set of enzymes indicating that the metabolic route did not pass via costunolide (Table 1). When HaES was replaced with CYP71BL9, there was mainly costunolide, only very little inunolide, and 8β-hydroxy-cyclocostunolide derivatives. This indicates, that with CYP71BL9, in the first step, costunolide was produced which subsequently was converted to eupatolide by the 8β-hydroxylation of HaG8H. In yeast and plant expression systems, it has already been reported that acid-induced rearrangement can be observed for GAA, 8βhydroxy-GAA and inunolide, but not for the 6,7-cis lactone costunolide (

; 

; 

; 

). So far, for the biosynthesis of STL in 
Asteraceae
only linear pathways have been elucidated (

; 

; 

), while the different pattern of rearrangement products here, clearly indicated two possible independent pathways leading to the same core STL skeleton.

Regarding the amino acid sequence, CYP71BL9/HaCOS is more similar to HaG8H than to the so far published costunolide synthases from other 
Asteraceae
. The substrate recognition site 5 (SRS5) is one of the most important regions for substrate specificity, especially position five after the KETLR/ExxR motiv which is closest to the catalytic center (

) (Fig. S6). All costunolide synthases that have so far been described share a Prolin and Valin amino acid on positions 4 and 5 while HaG8H and HaCOS have a Valin and a free position there. The loss of a conserved Prolin rest at Pos 4 together with an amino acid substitution at position 5 after the ExxR motiv is reported to change the substrate speficity and enzyme function in the closely relatey subfamily CYP71AJ (

). As HaCOS differs in this crucial region, there might be a different mechanism of substrate binding in the catalytic center. Generally, docking the substrates of multiple sesquiterpene oxidizing cytochrome p450s to the catalytic center of their respective enzymes as it has recently been performed for monoterpenes (

) could shed light on this aspect of cytochrome p450 function in future studies.

The expression pattern in the public transcriptome database revealed that CYP71BL9 is mainly expressed in bracts and leaves. The surface of bracts, though densly covered by linear an nonglandular trichomes, is lacking CGT and on leaves and florets it was shown, that the biosynthesis of STL in CGT is restricted to a very early and short period of organ development (

; 

). Moreover, CYP71BL9 was not reported from ESTs of capitate galdular trichomes (CGT) in the previous study of HaG8H (CYP71BL1) (

). This was confirmed by our own studies on trichome-based transcription of P450 genes in sunflower (

) and corroborates with the fact, that so far no costunolide was found in trichomes of the plant (

; 

). This implies that CYP71BL9 is part of an independent route of STL production in the inner tissues of sunflower, where small amounts of costunolide and dehydrostcostuslactone were found along with two xanthanolides (

). We found a very similar variant of CYP71BL9, “HaCos_var” (Fig. S6), expressed in sunflower seedlings, where it may be involved in the production of the inner STL. The function of these inner STL appears to be linked to plant growth processes in sunflower(

, 1997) and underlines that STL can be more than protective plant compounds with high toxicity (

).

Candidate gene fragments were retrieved from a public sunflower transcriptomic database (www.heliagene.org) and filtered by similarity to known P450 enzymes involved in 
Asteraceae STL
metabolism regarding amino acid identity and gene expression pattern as previously described (

). The whole open reading frame and UTS regions of CYP71BL9 was identified by 3′and 5′RACE (Clontech Laboratories, Inc., Mountain View, CA, 
USA
).

The cds of CYP71BL9 was amplified from bract cDNA using a proofreading polymerase, and cloned into the MCS1 site of the pESC-Ura plasmid using the primers
GTC AAT GAA TTC ATG GAG CCT TTC ACA ATT TTC TTC
and
GTC AAT ACT AGT CTA ATT TGG TTC TGA TAC GGA GAT AGG
. Amino acid sequences for phylogeny were aligned with BioEdit and a phylogeny was constructed with MEGA6 (1000 Bootstraps). CYP71BL9 and genes upstream in the biosynthetic pathway were inserted into the vector pLIFE33 by USER cloning as previously described (
;
;
).

Pathway reconstruction in 

Nicotiana benthamiana

and yeast was performed as described recently (

; 

). Extraction from yeast cultures was performed as previously described (

; 

; 

) and enzyme products were purified from 0.5 mL cultures by preparative HPLC.
